
Key contradiction / Error
1.Missing startup entry file:Create a new main.py file in the backend/app directory (as the startup entry point)
{
# Import the app (Flask application object) from the __init__.py file in the current directory from . import app

# Startup Entry: When main.py is run directly, the service is started. if __name__ == '__main__':
app.run(host='127.0.0.1', port=5000, debug=True)
}
2.Modify backend/app/__init__.py (retain only the Flask initialization, remove the startup code)
The previous code placed the startup logic in __init__.py. Python treats backend.app as a "package" rather than an "executable module", 
so it prompts "cannot be directly executed". By adding main.py as a dedicated startup entry point, Python can correctly recognize and start the service.
3.This error is a typical case of circular import: backend/app/__init__.py and backend/api/xxx_api.py import each other, causing Python to fail in module initialization. Specifically:
app/__init__.py imports the api module (from ..api import ...)
while api/login_api.py imports the app object (from ..app import app)
This forms a "app→api→app" loop, resulting in import failure. Please note that need to modify the interface files.
